    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok i think i get the coin thing but the \"spooky\" part is what's tripping me up. can u explain why people call it spooky? like why can't we just say it's like two socks that were always going to be a pair? why does it feel so weird or spooky to physicists?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"spooky\" part, as Einstein put it, is because it seems to violate the principle that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light. With your sock analogy, if you have a pair of socks, one red and one blue, and you send them to opposite ends of the galaxy, you *already know* what color the other is before you look. In the quantum world, however, the particles aren't *decided* on their properties until the moment of measurement.\n\nIt's not like the socks were secretly pre-programmed; it's like the particles are in a fuzzy, undecided state until one is observed, and *then* the other instantly snaps into the corresponding state, faster than any signal could travel between them. This instantaneous connection is what makes the physics community feel like it's bordering on the truly bizarre.",
      "source": "target",
