    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if they aren't programmed and there's no signal being sent, how does the second one \"know\" right away? it sounds like there's some hidden force or something invisible making it happen behind the scenes. is there any theory about what might actually be driving that connection?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's the million-dollar question, and it's where even the smartest physicists are still wrestling with the implications! Most interpretations suggest there isn't a \"hidden force\" in the classical sense, which is what makes it so frustrating. The idea of a hidden variable—some secret instruction set carried by the particles—was a popular thought, but experiments (like Bell tests) have strongly suggested that these hidden variables don't exist.\n\nInstead, the prevailing view is that the particles are fundamentally described by a single, shared quantum state. They aren't two separate entities communicating; they are one interconnected system, even when spatially separated. It’s less like two separate things talking, and more like one single, stretched-out entity.",
      "source": "target",
